On a height which rises to the right stand two villages, Cantalupo and Bardela; the latter is supposed to be the Mandela, which the poet describes as rugosus frigore pagus ; and, certes, it stands in an airy position, at the point of junction of the two valleys. You soon come to a small stream, of no remarkable character, but it is the Digentia, the gelidus rivus, at which the poet was wont to slake his thirst -me quoties reficit—and which flows away through the meadows to the foot of the said hill of Bardela—quem Man- dela bibit. You are now in the Sabine valley, so fondly loved and highly prized.

Cur valle permutem Sabina Divitias operosiores?

Why would l exchange burdensome riches for my Sabine valley.
